Abstract = {Inflation faced by many countries is rising continuously and remains a
   threat to the world economy. As prices rise, the demand for cheap stolen
   goods grows, strengthening incentives to increase the supply of stolen
   merchandise and thus increasing property crimes. With artificial
   intelligence gaining popularity, random forest, a machine learning model
   with ensemble learning properties, is selected to perform a dominance
   analysis of the impact of headline inflation on property crimes. Two
   datasets from timelines 2011-2019 in Northern Mindanao (Region X)
   Philippines were utilized: (1) The headline consumer price index (11
   Goods and Services), and (2) The indexed property crimes (4 crimes).
   Four random forest models are developed to determine the level of
   dominance of the major goods and services in terms of their impact on
   each of the property crimes. The following are the models:},
